ncoln Pulsepoint user first to start CPR on person in cardiac arrest|url=https://journalstar.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/lincoln-pulsepoint-user-first-to-start-cpr-on-person-in/article_a949a46c-7877-5dc8-9532-16f9bcef63dd.html|website=Lincoln Journal Star|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Livermore-Pleasanton Fire Department]]<ref name=LPFD>{{cite web|title=Livermore, Pleasanton Heroes Save Marin Man In Cardiac Arrest|url=https://patch.com/california/pleasanton/livermore-pleasanton-heroes-save-marin-man-cardiac-arrest|website=Patch|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Long Beach Fire Department (California)]]<ref name=LBFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint helps save lives in first year|url=https://journalstar.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/pulsepoint-helps-save-lives-in-first-year/article_87c2487f-0b39-5ce1-a039-6f0945e4a497.html|website=Journal Star|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Los Angeles County Fire Department]]<ref name=LACFD/>\n* [[Los Angeles Fire Department]]<ref name=LAFD/>\n* [[Madison Fire Department]]<ref name=MFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint|url=https://www.cityofmadison.com/fire/your-safety/pulsepoint|website=City of Madison, WI|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Marin County]] Fire Department\n* [[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina]]<ref name=MEDIC>{{cite web|title=Mecklenburg County Rolls Out CPR Smart-Phone App|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/nc/charlotte/news/2019/01/24/mecklenburg-county-rolls-out-cpr-smart-phone-app|website=Spectrum News North Carolina|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n* Miami Beach Fire Department<ref name=MBFD>{{cite web|title=Miami Beach uses app to alert bystanders of sudden cardiac arrest|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-beach/article72555272.html|website=Miami Herald|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Milwaukee Fire Department]]<ref name=MFDWI>{{cite web|title=Milwaukee joins cities across nation using PulsePoint: \u2018Be better neighbors and better responders\u2019|url=https://fox6now.com/2019/11/26/milwaukee-joins-cities-across-nation-using-pulsepoint-be-better-neighbors-and-better-responders/|website=WITI-TV FOX6 News|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Naperville Fire Department]]<ref name=NapervilleFD>{{cite web|title=New city app allows volunteers to help in cardiac emergencies|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/ct-nvs-naperville-fire-department-app-st-0722-20160720-story.html|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Norfolk Fire Rescue<ref name=NFR>{{cite web|title=The City of Norfolk is now a PulsePoint-enabled community|url=https://www.norfolk.gov/index.aspx?NID=4102|website=City of Norfolk, Virginia|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Orange County Fire Authority]]<ref name=OCFA>{{cite web|title=OCFA Launches Free PulsePoint Mobile App for Citizen CPR Response|url=https://www.ocfa.org/Uploads/NewsRelease/OCFA%20PulsePoint%20Public%20Release.pdf|website=Orange County Fire Authority|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Orange County Fire Rescue]]<ref name=OCFR>{{cite web|title=Orange County Fire Rescue Launches Lifesaving Apps With Technology to Help Keep Hearts Healthy|url=https://newsroom.ocfl.net/media-advisories/press-releases/2017/02/orange-county-fire-rescue-launches-lifesaving-apps-with-technology-to-help-keep-hearts-healthy/|website=Orange County Government Florida|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Orlando Fire Department]]<ref name=OrlandoFD>{{cite web|title=Download PulsePoint App, Help Provide Life-Saving Assistance|url=http://www.cityoforlando.net/blog/download-pulsepoint-app-help-provide-life-saving-assistance/|website=City of Orlando|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Palm Beach County Fire Rescue]]<ref name=PBCFR>{{cite web|title=Palm Beach Gardens Honors 2 Women Who Used App To Save A Life|url=https://wjno.iheart.com/featured/local-news-wire/content/2018-04-05-palm-beach-gardens-honors-2-women-who-used-app-to-save-a-life/|website=1290 WJNO|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Pittsburgh Bureau of Fire]]<ref name=PBF>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint App Alerts Nearby Citizens To Cardiac Arrest Patients In Need Of Aid|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2017/11/03/pulse-point-app-cariac-arrest-alerts/|website=KDKA-TV News CBS Pittsburgh|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Plano Fire-Rescue]]<ref name=PlanoFR>{{cite web|title=New Plano Smart Phone App Will Save Lives|url=https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2015/04/20/officials-new-plano-smart-phone-app-will-save-lives|website=CBS Local DFW|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Portland Fire & Rescue]]<ref name=PFR>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Apps|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/fire/article/544086|website=City of Portland|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Prince George's County Fire/EMS Department]]<ref name=VCFD>{{cite web|title=Pr. George's County rolls out CPR app that could save lives|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/pr-georges-county-rolls-out-cpr-app-that-could-save-lives/2016/10/12/f7f6e3b0-9095-11e6-9c85-ac42097b8cc0_story.html?noredirect=on|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Prince William County Department of Fire and Rescue]]<ref name=PWCDFR>{{cite web|title=Community Safety - PulsePoint|url=https://www.pwcgov.org/government/dept/FR/Pages/pulsepoint.aspx|website=Prince William County, Virginia|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Rapid City Fire Department<ref name=RapidCityFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint one year later|url=https://www.newscenter1.tv/pulsepoint-one-year-later/|website=KNBN NewsCenter1|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Reno Fire Department<ref name=RenoFD>{{cite web|title=Lifesaving PulsePoint app now available in Reno|url=https://mynews4.com/news/local/lifesaving-pulsepoint-app-now-available-in-reno|website=KRNV TV News 4|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Richmond Fire Department (Virginia)<ref name=RichmondVAFD>{{cite web|title=City Partners With PulsePoint to Improve Cardiac Arrest Response in RVA|url=https://richmondvaannouncements.blogspot.com/2016/04/city-partners-with-pulsepoint-to.html|website=Richmond City News|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sacramento Fire Department]]<ref name=SacramentoFD>{{cite web|title=Sac Fire Department Launches PulsePoint Respond App|url=https://sacramentocityexpress.com/2015/12/17/sac-fire-department-launches-pulsepoint-respond-app/|website=City Express|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sacramento Metropolitan Fire District]]<ref name=MetroFire>{{cite web|title=Launch of PulsePoint Application Next Step in Life-saving Outreach|url=https://www.metrofire.ca.gov/index.php/news-releases/695-pulsepoint-launched|website=Sacramento Metropolitan Fire District|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Salem Fire Department<ref name=SalemFD>{{cite web|title=Save a Life with the PulsePoint Responder App|url=https://www.cityofsalem.net/Pages/save-a-life-with-the-pulsepoint-responder-app.aspx|website=City of Salem, Oregon|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[San Bernardino County Fire Department]]<ref name=SBCoFD>{{cite web|title=Get the app. Save a life.|url=https://www.sbcfire.org/Programs/PulsePoint.aspx|website=San Bernardino County|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[San Diego Fire-Rescue Department]]<ref name=SDFD>{{cite web|title=County, City, Fire Partners Activate CPR App|url=https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/sdcfa/san-diego-county-pulse-point.html|website=San Diego County|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[San Jose Fire Department]]<ref name=SJFD/>\n* [[San Luis Obispo Fire Department]]<ref name=SLOFD>{{cite web|title=California man helps save woman thanks to phone app|url=https://www.wthr.com/article/california-man-helps-save-woman-thanks-phone-app|website=WTHR TV 13|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[San Ramon Valley Fire Protection District]]<ref name=SRVFPD>{{cite web|title=Life-Saving 'Fire Department CPR' App Going National|url=https://www.govtech.com/public-safety/Lifesaving-Fire-Department-CPR-App-Going-National.html|website=Government Technology|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Santa Barbara County Fire Department]]<ref name=SBCFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint App Available to County|url=https://www.edhat.com/site/tidbit.cfm?nid=154753|website=EdHat|publisher=[[Santa Barbara County Fire Department]]|accessdate=25 June 2015|date=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Santa Clara County Fire Department]]<ref name=SCCFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Mobile App|url=http://www.sccfd.org/education-and-preparedness-overview/safety-information-referral-assistance/pulse-point-mobile-app|website=Santa Clara County Fire Department|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Seattle Fire Department]]<ref name=SFD>{{cite web|title=Save a life around the corner: This app turns Seattle bystanders into first responders|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/cpr-app-turns-seattle-bystanders-into-first-responders/|website=The Seattle Times|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Seminole County Fire Department]]<ref name=Seminole>{{cite web|title=Seminole joins PulsePoint app that alerts CPR-trained bystanders to cardiac arrest victims|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/seminole-county/os-ne-seminole-county-pulse-point-app-20191023-qxkjgast3rehnbq4zkm5vcpbp4-story.html|website=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Sioux Falls Fire Rescue<ref name=SFFR>{{cite web|title=Sioux Falls Residents Use App to Help Save Lives|url=https://www.kdlt.com/2018/05/24/sioux-falls-residents-use-app-help-save-lives/|website=KDLT NBC TV|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sonoma County Fire District]]<ref name=SonomaCoFD>{{cite web|title=New PulsePoint Respond app tracks whereabouts of first responders who can help with CPR|url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/lifestyle/8878882-181/new-pulsepoint-response-app-tracks|website=The Press Democrat|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* South Bend Fire Department<ref name=SouthBendFD>{{cite web|title=Mobile app connects South Bend-area users with cardiac arrest victims|url=https://www.southbendtribune.com/news/publicsafety/mobile-app-connects-south-bend-area-users-with-cardiac-arrest/article_2ecd0327-fade-5780-b47f-3f005628136a.html|website=South Bend Tribune|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Spokane Fire Department<ref name=SpokaneFD>{{cite web|title=Spokane FD Verified Responder|url=https://vimeo.com/340216713|website=Vimeo (PulsePoint Foundation)|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Suffolk County Department of Fire, Rescue and Emergency Services<ref name=SCFRES>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint App Launched With The Intent To Help Save Lives|url=https://suffolkcountyny.gov/Departments/FRES/Pulse-Point|website=Suffolk County Government|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Tualatin Valley Fire and Rescue]]<ref name=TVFR>{{cite web|title=Fact Sheet 2015|url=http://www.tvfr.com/DocumentCenter/View/7|website=Tualatin Valley Fire & Rescue|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n* Tucson Fire Department<ref name=TucsonFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint. Get the Point, Save a Life|url=https://www.tucsonaz.gov/fire/pulsepoint|website=City of Tucson|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ventura County Fire Department]]<ref name=VCoFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint App now available to Ventura County|url=http://www.vcfd.org/about-vcfd/pulsepoint-information|website=Ventura County Fire Department|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Virginia Beach Department of Emergency Medical Services]]<ref name=VBEMS>{{cite web|title=YOU can help save a life!|url=https://www.vbems.com/pulsepoint/|website=Virginia Beach Department of Emergency Medical Services|accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Winnipeg Fire Paramedic Service]]<ref name=WFPS>{{cite web|title=WFPS Community Relations - PulsePoint|url=https://winnipeg.ca/FPS/CommunityRelations/PulsePoint.stm|website=City of Winnipeg|accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.pulsepoint.org/ PulsePoint Website]\n*[https://web.pulsepoint.org/ PulsePoint Web Client]\n*[https://aedregistry.pulsepoint.org/ PulsePoint AED Registry]\n*[https://twitter.com/pulsepoint @PulsePoint (Twitter)]\n*[https://apps.apple.com/us/app/pulsepoint/id500772134 PulsePoint Respond on App Store]\n*[https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=mobi.firedepartment PulsePoint Respond on Google Play]\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|mobile phone application}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = PulsePoint\n| title                  = PulsePoint Respond\n| logo                   = LogoForPulsePointApplication.png\n| logo caption           = \n| logo size              = \n| logo alt               = \n| collapsible            = \n| screenshot             = PulsePoint App v4-7 Incident List on iPhone XS 04-18-2020.png\n| caption                = \n| screenshot size        = \n| screenshot alt         = \n| author                 = Richard Price\n| developer              = PulsePoint Foundation\n| released               = 2011 (iOS) ; 2012 (Android)\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version <!-- List platforms officially developed by PulsePoint Foundation --> = {{Multiple releases\n|branch1 = Android\n|version1 = 4.7\n|date1 = {{Start date and age|2020|04|17}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=mobi.firedepartment|title=PulsePoint Respond|website=Google Play|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n|branch2 = iOS\n|version2 = 4.7\n|date2 = {{Start date and age|2020|04|17}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/us/app/pulsepoint/id500772134|title=PulsePoint Respond|website=App Store|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n  }}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = \n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = English, Spanish, French, Japanese\n| language count         = \n| language footnote      = \n| genre                  = \n| license                = \n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|https://www.pulsepoint.org|pulsepoint.org}}\n| standard               = \n| AsOf                   = \n}}\n[[File:PulsePoint App v4-3 CPR Needed on iPhone XS 05-22-2019.png|thumb|PulsePoint Respond CPR needed activation screen indicating responder, AED and victim location]]\n[[File:PulsePoint App v4-3 AED detail on iPhone XS 05-23-2019.png|thumb|PulsePoint Respond AED detail screen showing colocated bleeding control and Epinephrine resources in [[Howard County Department of Fire and Rescue Services]]]]\n'''PulsePoint''' is a 911-connected [[mobile phone]] [[Application software|application]] that allows users to view and receive alerts on calls being responded to by [[fire departments]] and [[emergency medical services]]. The app's main feature, and where its name comes from, is that it sends alerts to users at the same time that [[dispatcher]]s are sending the call to emergency crews.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Eryn|title=L.A. County Fire Department links dispatch system to PulsePoint CPR app|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/countygovernment/la-me-cpr-app-20140807-story.html|accessdate=15 January 2015|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=6 August 2014}}</ref> The goal is to increase the possibility that a victim in [[cardiac arrest]] will receive [[cardiopulmonary resuscitation]] (CPR) quickly. The app uses the current location of a user and will alert them if someone in their vicinity is in need of CPR.<ref name=WHNT>{{cite news|last1=Killimayer|first1=Christine|title=Madison Fire & Rescue needs help raising funds to bring lifesaving 'Pulse Point' app to Madison County|url=http://whnt.com/2014/12/26/madison-fire-rescue-needs-help-raising-funds-to-bring-lifesaving-pulse-point-app-to-madison-county/|accessdate=15 January 2015|agency=WHNT News|date=26 December 2014}}</ref> The app, which interfaces with a fire department's dispatch center, will send notifications to users only if the victim is in a public place and only to users that are in the immediate vicinity of the emergency.<ref name=WHNT/> In February 2017, PulsePoint introduced a professional version called Verified Responder that also alerts in residential settings.<ref name=VRTVFR>{{cite web|title=Pilot Program Leverages Off-Duty Professional Firefighters, Technology and Defibrillators to Save Lives|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/2017/02/14/pilot-program-leverages-off-duty-professional-firefighters-technology-and-defibrillators-to-save-lives/|website=PulsePoint|accessdate=5 December 2018|date=2017-02-15}}</ref> Based in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]], PulsePoint is run by a public 501(c)(3) non-profit foundation of the same name.<ref name=SJFD>{{cite news|title=New Mobile Phone App To Help Save Lives Announced By San Jos\u00e9 Fire Department And El Camino Hospital|url=http://www.pulsepoint.org/2012/02/14/new-mobile-phone-app-to-help-save-lives-announced-by-san-jose-fire-department-and-el-camino-hospital/|accessdate=15 January 2015|date=February 14, 2012}}</ref> As of January 30, 2020, the foundation reported that connected agencies had requested the assistance of 350,000 nearby responders for 100,000 cardiac arrest events.<ref name=PulsePoint>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Respond Activation Statistics|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/stats/|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=30 January 2020|date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"Our mission is to make it much easier for citizens who are trained in CPR to use their life-saving skills to save lives. Through the use of modern, location-aware mobile devices, PulsePoint is building applications that work with local public safety agencies to improve communications with citizens and empower them to help reduce the millions of annual deaths from sudden cardiac arrest.\"<ref name=PPF>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Foundation Mission|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/foundation/|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=5 December 2018|date=2014-07-24}}</ref>}}\n\nIn addition to Android and iOS, PulsePoint offers a web client at {{URL|https://web.pulsepoint.org|web.pulsepoint.org}} that allows users to view the same data that appears in PulsePoint Respond with a browser. PulsePoint uses a standardized set of incident types normalized across Public Safety Answering Points (PSAP) and Computer-aided Dispatch (CAD) system vendors.<ref name=PulsePointIncidentTypes>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Incident Types|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/incident-types/|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=19 August 2019|date=2019-08-18}}</ref> The foundation also underwrites an automated external defibrillator (AED) app and registry to provide location information to PulsePoint responders and dispatchers.<ref name=PulsePointAED>{{cite web|title=Designed to put AEDs in motion|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/pulsepoint-aed/|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=10 December 2018|date=2014-07-24}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the PulsePoint Respond app was approved by the [[First Responder Network Authority]] (FirstNet) and added to the App Catalog.<ref name=FirstNet>{{cite web|title=GPS Technology Delivers Critical Lifeline for First Responders|url=https://firstnet.gov/newsroom/blog/gps-technology-delivers-critical-lifeline-first-responders|website=First Responder Network Authority (FirstNet)|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nRichard Price, president of the PulsePoint Foundation, said that the idea for the application came to him in 2010 while he was serving as the fire chief in the [[San Ramon Valley]].<ref name=NBC>{{cite news|last1=Aleccia|first1=Jonel|title=Heart Attack Rescue? There's an App for That|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/heart-attack-rescue-theres-app-n121911|accessdate=17 January 2015|agency=NBC News|date=3 June 2014}}</ref> While he was out to lunch he heard sirens and saw one of his own engines pull up in front of the restaurant he was dining in.<ref name=LAFD>{{cite news|last1=Hartley|first1=Eric|title='PulsePoint' app, which helps people get lifesaving CPR, coming to L.A.|url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130130/pulsepoint-app-which-helps-people-get-lifesaving-cpr-coming-to-la|accessdate=15 January 2015|agency=Los Angeles Daily News|date=January 29, 2013}}</ref>  It turned out that someone next door had collapsed and gone into [[cardiac arrest]]. Since Price was the department chief, he was not dispatched to the call and did not know about it, but he was CPR certified and carried a [[defibrillator]] in his car.<ref name=LAFD/> This incident left him wondering if technology could help produce a way for civilians who were trained to help in the event of a nearby emergency.  The [[American Heart Association]] estimates that 383,000 out of hospital [[cardiac arrest]]s occur each year in the United States.<ref name=AHA>{{cite web|title=CPR & Sudden Cardiac Arrest (SCA) Fact Sheet|url=http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/CPRAndECC/WhatisCPR/CPRFactsandStats/CPR-Statistics_UCM_307542_Article.jsp|website=American Heart Association|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, PulsePoint was one of only five [[mobile application]]s worldwide to be nominated for a [[Webby Award]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Creaven|first1=Patrick|title=San Ramon Valley Cardiac Arrest App Nominated For a Webby Award|url=http://patch.com/california/sanramon/san-ramon-valley-cardiac-arrest-app-nominated-for-a-webby-award|accessdate=15 January 2015|agency=San Ramon Patch}}</ref> It was nominated under the category of ''Best Use of GPS or Location Technology''. A year later, in 2013, it was once again nominated in the same category.<ref>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint - Nominee|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2013/mobile-apps/all-devices/best-use-of-gps-or-location-technology/pulsepoint/|website=The Webby Awards|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> In 2014, the application was once again nominated, this time in the category of ''City & Urban Innovation''.<ref>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint - 2014 Nominee|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2014/mobile-apps/handheld-devices/city-urban-innovation/pulsepoint|website=The Webby Awards|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== AED Registry ==\nAlong with the intention of getting CPR started faster and more often, a key objective of the PulsePoint Respond app is to inform those near a cardiac arrest event of the location of [[Automated External Defibrillator]]s (AED) in the immediate vicinity of the victim.<ref name=SpokaneValleyCityHallAED>{{cite web|title=Spokane Valley City Hall to join defibrillator sites|url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2014/apr/12/spokane-valley-city-hall-to-join-defibrillator/|website=The Spokesman-Review|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> To accomplish this, the PulsePoint Foundation maintains an on\u2011demand (cloud-based) registry of AED locations and encourages anyone to contribute device locations.<ref name=RegistryECH>{{cite web|title=El Camino Hospital Collaborates with PulsePoint Foundation to Launch Crowd-Sourced Automated External Defibrillator (AED) Registry|url=https://www.elcaminohealth.org/news/el-camino-hospital-collaborates-pulsepoint-foundation-launch-crowd-sourced-automated-external|website=El Camino Hospital|accessdate=17 September 2019|date=2015-01-02}}</ref> This crowdsourced AED location information is subsequently reviewed by local public safety agencies with support from the foundation.<ref name=SanDiegoCoAEDs>{{cite web|title=San Diego County, City, Fire Chiefs Launch AED App, Crowdsourcing Campaign|url=https://www.countynewscenter.com/county-city-fire-chiefs-launch-aed-app-crowdsourcing-campaign/|website=County News Center, County of San Diego Communications Office|accessdate=17 September 2019|date=2015-03-16}}</ref> Approved AEDs are then shown to responders and dispatchers during cardiac emergencies. All aspects of the registry are provided free of charge.<ref name=PPCost>{{cite web|title=FAQ: What are the costs involved in implementing the app?|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/pulsepoint-respond/#faqs|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=17 September 2019|date=2014-07-23}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2017, the PulsePoint Foundation announced a partnership with Priority Dispatch Corporation to allow dispatchers to inform callers of the location of nearby AEDs when the [[Medical Priority Dispatch System]] deemed them necessary.<ref name=PDC>{{cite web|title=Nearest AED to be integrated into medical dispatch protocols|url=https://www.ems1.com/ems-products/aeds/articles/nearest-aed-to-be-integrated-into-medical-dispatch-protocols-CINaMfcnNT6GUlvW/|website=EMS1|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 PulsePoint extended the registry to include other colocated resources including [[Naloxone]] (e.g., Narcan\u00ae) and [[Epinephrine]] (e.g., [[EpiPen]]\u00ae), along with Bleeding Control Kits.<ref name=RespondUpdateJune2019>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Respond June 2019 Update|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/2019/05/31/pulsepoint-respond-june-2019/|website=PulsePoint Foundation|accessdate=19 September 2019|date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n== Concerns ==\nSome privacy experts have expressed concern that the app may invade the [[medical privacy]] of victims.<ref name=NBC/> The [[Los Angeles County Fire Department]], one of the many users of the app, has pointed out that The [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act]] ([[HIPAA]]) protects the privacy of identifiable health information.<ref name=LACFD>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint App Now Available to Los Angeles County|url=http://www.fire.lacounty.gov/lacofd-pulse-point/|website=LACFD|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>  On a \u2018CPR Needed\u2019 notification, which is sent out through the app, the only information that is seen is an address (which must be in a public place) and a business name, if available. The individually identifiable health information protected by [[HIPAA]], such as name, birth date, or [[Social Security number|SSN]] are not reported or even known by the PulsePoint application.<ref name=LACFD/>\n\nAdditional concerns that have been raised are that the app can cause too many bystanders to congregate at the scene of an emergency and that those responding via the app may not be trained in [[CPR]] or [[Automated external defibrillator|AED]].<ref name=Sioux>{{cite web|title=Sioux Falls Pulse Point|url=http://www.siouxfalls.org/fire/professional-standards/pulse-point.aspx|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2018, the [[International Association of Fire Chiefs]] (IAFC) issued a Position Statement on PulsePoint.<ref name=IAFC>{{cite web|title=Using Mobile Technology to Increase Cardiac Arrest Survival Rates|url=https://www.iafc.org/about-iafc/positions/position/using-mobile-technology-to-increase-cardiac-arrest-survival-rates|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nAlong with being able to view a list of calls in real time, users also have the option to listen in to radio traffic to accompany the application\u2019s incident list.<ref name=Tech>{{cite web|title=Technical Information|url=http://www.pulsepoint.org/implementation/|website=PulsePoint|publisher=PulsePoint|accessdate=15 January 2015|date=2014-07-24}}</ref> During a CPR-needed response, this functionality allows citizen and off-duty rescuers to hear the dispatcher update emergency responders regarding patient location, scene conditions, etc.<ref name=RespondUpdateJune2019/> To facilitate the live feed, PulsePoint uses Broadcastify, a website that is the largest broadcaster of live public safety audio feeds, to stream radio channels within the app.<ref name=Tech/>\n\nOn December 11, 2018, PulsePoint released v4.1 for iOS<ref name=v4-1>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint Respond December 2018 Update|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/2018/12/07/pulsepoint-respond-december-2018/|accessdate=18 December 2018|date=2018-12-08}}</ref> that included the ability to override a device's Do Not Disturb setting and play an alert sound even when the device is muted for \u201cCPR Needed\u201d alerts.<ref name=Critical-Alerts>{{cite web|title=Critical Alerts|url=https://www.pulsepoint.org/critical-alerts/|accessdate=18 December 2018|date=2018-11-25}}</ref> This required a special entitlement from Apple.<ref name=entitlement>{{cite web|title=The authorization status to play sounds for critical alerts.|url=https://developer.apple.com/documentation/usernotifications/unnotificationsettings/2963116-criticalalertsetting/|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn additional feature of the application is an interface with [[Flickr]] that allows agencies to share photos through the app. Users can view incident, event, station, apparatus, and other photos that the agency chooses to share.<ref name=Tech/>\n\n== Users ==\n{{Expand list|date=June 2015}}\nAs of January 2020 the dispatch centers in more than 3,800 communities were connected to PulsePoint.<ref name=PulsePoint/> Some of the most well known agencies include:\n<!-- ONLY INCLUDE DEPARTMENTS WITH A CITED SOURCE AND THAT HAVE A WIKIPEDIA PAGE  --> \n* Akron Fire Department<ref name=AkronFD>{{cite web|title=City of Akron launches life-saving PulsePoint app|url=https://fox8.com/2018/05/31/city-of-akron-launches-life-saving-pulsepoint-app/|website=FOX 8 TV Cleveland|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Alameda County Fire Department]]<ref name=ACFD>{{cite web|title=Community Services - PulsePoint|url=https://www.acgov.org/fire/community/pulsepoint.htm|website=Alameda County Fire Department|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Albuquerque Fire Rescue<ref name=ABQFR>{{cite web|title=Albuquerque Fire Rescue - PulsePoint|url=https://www.cabq.gov/fire/pulsepoint|website=City of Albuquerque|accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Anne Arundel County Fire Department<ref name=AACFD>{{cite web|title=Help Save a Life: PulsePoint Now in Anne Arundel County|url=https://living.aahs.org/heart-vascular/help-save-a-life-pulsepoint-now-in-anne-arundel-county/|website=Anne Arundel Medical Center|accessdate=16 September 2019|date=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n* [[Atlanta Fire Rescue Department]]<ref name=AFRD>{{cite web|title=Atlanta Fire Rescue Department Quarterly Report|url=http://citycouncil.atlantaga.gov/Home/ShowDocument?id=346|website=Atlanta City Council|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Bloomington Fire Department<ref name=BLOOM>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint app now available in Monroe County|url=https://www.hoosiertimes.com/herald_times_online/news/local/pulsepoint-app-now-available-in-monroe-county/article_278a01c3-b324-53a2-847a-63bf1228da6f.html|website=Hoosier Times|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Brevard County Fire Rescue<ref name=BREVARDCOFR>{{cite web|title=Brevard County Welcomes PulsePoint|url=https://www.brevardfl.gov/FireRescue/EMSOps/pulse-point|website=Brevard County|accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[British Columbia Ambulance Service]]<ref name=BCEHS>{{cite web|title=New smartphone app could save lives|url=http://www.bcehs.ca/about/news-stories/news-releases/2018/new-smartphone-app-could-save-lives|website=Provincial Health Services Authority (PHSA)|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection]]<ref name=CALFIRE>{{cite web|title=County Fire Dept Connects to Life-Saving App|url=https://calfireslo.org/2019/07/22/county-fire-dept-connects-to-life-saving-app/|website=San Luis Obispo County Fire Department|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Chesapeake Fire Department]]<ref name=ChesapeakeFD>{{cite web|title=Who's Life Will You Save Today?|url=http://www.cityofchesapeake.net/government/city-departments/departments/fire/ems/PulsePoint.htm|website=City of Chesapeake|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* City of Casa Grande Fire Department<ref>https://casagrandeaz.gov/cgfd-kicks-off-cpr-awareness-week-with-launch-of-aed-campaign/.</ref>\n* [[Clark County Fire Department (Nevada)]]<ref name=CCFDNV>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint app, used in Las Vegas Valley, can be lifesaver|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/local-las-vegas/pulsepoint-app-used-in-las-vegas-valley-can-be-lifesaver-1604931/|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=12 September 2019|date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland EMS]]<ref name=CEMS>{{cite web|title=How a Smartphone App Can Help You Save a Life|url=https://health.clevelandclinic.org/how-a-smartphone-app-can-help-you-save-a-life/|website=Cleveland Clinic|accessdate=19 August 2019|date=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n* Columbus Division of Fire<ref name=CDOF>{{cite web|title=Know CPR? Willing to save a life? Download PulsePoint today!|url=https://www.columbus.gov/public-safety/fire/safety-information/PulsePoint/|website=City of Columbus|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Coral Springs Fire Department]]<ref name=CSFD>{{cite web|title=CTIA Wireless Foundation Sponsors PulsePoint Launch in Coral Springs|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z9OUjO77dFw|website=YouTube|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department]]<ref name=DCFEMS>{{cite web|title=Mayor Bowser Announces New Life-Saving Technologies|url=https://fems.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-announces-new-life-saving-technologies|website=DC.gov|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n* El Paso Fire Department<ref name=EPFDTX>{{cite web|title=PulsePoint app now available in El Paso|url=https://www.elpasotexas.gov/fire%20department%20section/fire-department/news/2019/01/07/pulse-point|website=City of El Paso|accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Fort Lauderdale Fire-Rescue Department]]<ref name=FLFR>{{cite web|title=How to Save a Life with CPR App|url=https://wsvn.com/news/how-to-save-a-life-with-cpr-app|website=WSVN-TV|access